[02:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'yourself. So, first thing is like why do you even need X42? It\'s good to know what the problem is so you choose the right tool for the right solution. So the big problem with'

[03:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'payments on the internet right now is that even though we did a lot of layering to make it feel pretty fast and pretty seamless, it actually goes'

[03:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'through like insanely old systems that take forever to settle to move the money around. Sometimes it gets paused. There\'s a lot of middleman. There\'s a'

[03:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'lot of fees. Uh and there\'s a lot of trust required. I was just talking to someone earlier um from the hackathon, hackathon participant. I was saying um they accept this like $1 donation for'

[03:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'their mini game that they did and it\'s through PayPal. And like PayPal, you would think like, you know, pretty modern and stuff, all good, but they actually take a 56 cent fee on $1.'

[03:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So the donation they get is actually 44 cents instead of a dollar. That\'s insane. Um, and so it\'s impossible to do microp payments on the internet because'

[04:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of it. Because of this archic system. This is where it shows the most because the archic system is not good to move small amounts of money. And then we live in a world where agents are starting to'

[04:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'become a major player in the internet. There\'s a wave of them coming. They they can do all sort of things and they cannot use this archaic system. It\'s not it\'s not for them. They need a internet'

[04:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'native payment system. And so this is where X42 shines in my opinion. I summarize it as it\'s a universal language for internet payments.'

[04:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'It\'s a language that everybody understands that you can talk through simple HTTP and both parties can now agree on an exchange. I pay you this'

[05:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'amount, you give me this product. And there is no trust. There\'s no preset of accounts or credit cards somewhere uh prior to this exchange. There\'s no keys'

[05:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'required and it\'s instant payments. Immediately the payment is settled as soon as I give you the result and it\'s super super low fees. So it\'s great for'

[05:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'humans and it\'s great for agents. And so this is why it got so much excitement in the community and uh we think it\'s like going to be a big part of the internet'

[05:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'uh in the coming years. So real quick how it works. This is like the simplified view on it on the consumer side. The payer does a request an HTTP request to your service. The'

[05:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'service says hey this service costs money. So it returns a 402 response. This is where the whole X42 comes from is the 402 HTTP error code. The consumer'

[06:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'now understands this and reads the payment requirements and signs an authorization'

[06:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for you to withdraw that amount from their wallet effectively and sends that back to your API. Then the API just needs to take that authorization'

[06:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'put it on chain and that can be done by the API itself or it can be done through a facilitator. We\'ll talk about that. And the facilitator helps you actually finalize the payment. So consume that'

[06:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'authorization and then gives you back the hey this payment is done. It\'s all settled which then you can return the product back to the user. That\'s the basic flow. If you understand this, you understand most of X42. And this is why'

[06:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'um I think it got so much adoption because it\'s so simple. It\'s a very simple flow. So once you understand this, now let\'s go into something a bit'

